    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much space do I need for a commercial bakery kitchen in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">It depends on your production volume. A micro or home-based bakery producing 10–30 kg per day can operate in 200–400 sq ft (18–37 sq metres). A small commercial bakery producing 30–100 kg per day needs 500–1,000 sq ft (46–93 sq metres). A medium commercial bakery producing 100–300 kg per day requires 1,000–2,500 sq ft (93–232 sq metres). Industrial bakeries producing 300 kg+ per day typically need 2,500 sq ft or more. Always plan for some expansion room — kitchens that are tight on Day 1 become unworkable as production grows.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What are the FSSAI requirements for a bakery kitchen in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Key FSSAI requirements for bakery kitchens include: smooth non-absorbent washable floor and wall surfaces (typically food-grade anti-slip tiles on floors, ceramic tiles on walls to at least 1.5m height); dedicated hand-washing basins with soap and drying facilities; insect screens on all windows and openings; proper drainage with a grease trap; potable water supply with testing documentation; separate zones for raw ingredients and finished products; pest control documentation; and a food safety management plan. You'll also need a valid FSSAI registration or licence depending on your turnover. Read our full <a href="/blog/bakery-license-india">bakery licence guide</a> for complete documentation requirements.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the best layout for a small bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For a small bakery (500–1,000 sq ft), the most practical layout is typically an L-shape or U-shape. Ovens and heavy equipment go along one wall (the "hot wall") with the exhaust system above. Work tables form the L or U, with mixing equipment at one end and decorating/packaging at the other. Cold storage is positioned at the back, away from the hot wall. The key principle is unidirectional flow: ingredients come in, get processed, and finished product exits at the other end of the production sequence without backtracking. Even in a small space, maintaining this flow direction prevents collisions and cross-contamination.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much does it cost to design and fit out a bakery kitchen in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Kitchen fitout costs (excluding equipment) range from ₹8–12 lakh for a budget fitout of a 100 sq metre kitchen to ₹25–40 lakh for a premium fitout of the same space. Key cost elements are tiling (floor and walls), electrical works, plumbing and drainage, and ventilation/exhaust systems. Professional kitchen design fees add ₹50,000–₹2,00,000 depending on project scale but can save significantly more by preventing costly design errors. Equipment costs are separate and range from ₹8 lakh for a basic small commercial bakery setup to ₹60 lakh+ for a full medium production kitchen.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What ventilation does a commercial bakery kitchen need? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A commercial bakery kitchen needs an exhaust hood over every heat source (ovens, proofers, steamers), a properly sized exhaust duct system connected to an exterior exhaust point, and makeup air supply to prevent negative pressure. Target 30–40 air changes per hour (ACH) in the production area. For a 100 sq metre kitchen with 3m ceilings (300 cubic metres), you need a ventilation system capable of moving 9,000–12,000 cubic metres per hour. Have an HVAC engineer size the system — undersized ventilation leads to overheated kitchens, equipment failures, and staff health problems. Ventilation design must be finalised before construction since duct routing affects oven placement.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Where should the oven be placed in a bakery kitchen? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">The oven should be placed: (1) Against or near an exterior wall or below a roof access point, to minimise exhaust duct run length. (2) Adjacent to the proofing area, so proofed dough can be transferred directly to the oven without travelling across the kitchen. (3) With at minimum 1.5 metres of clear loading space in front — more (2–2.5m) for rotary rack ovens. (4) With adequate side and rear clearance for service access (typically 600mm). (5) In a group with other ovens sharing a common exhaust hood and duct if possible. Never place ovens in the centre of a kitchen if it can be avoided — this makes ventilation expensive and creates traffic flow problems.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

